The paper proposes an architecture for achieving telexistence and teleoperation of humanoid robots, which involves combining several technological set-ups, methodologies, locomotion and manipulation algorithms. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the human operator experience in terms of ability to adapt to the robot and to the architecture, which suggests that it may also belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of algorithms for locomotion and manipulation, which suggests that it may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the embodiment of the robot and uses experimental results, which suggests that it may belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes an architecture for achieving telexistence and teleoperation, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
